<div id="review_296190290" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/296190290" />
    <a title="Conor" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7197318-conor"><img alt="Conor" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1324357512p2/7197318.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/296190290?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Conor" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Conor" href="/user/show/7197318-conor">Conor</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer296190290" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8931671560622845429">Rating a correspondance between two historical figures is difficult. Character development and unity of theme with the corresondance as a whole can hardly be on the mind of a scholar defending his reputation or satiating a lover. Yet these are exactly the criteria I default to in rating anything that tells a story.<br/><br/>Yet the Letters of Abelard and Heloise earned four stars from me precisely because they made me forget that they are a historical correspondance. Abelard is a scholar before he is a th</span>
  <span id="freeText8931671560622845429" style="display:none">Rating a correspondance between two historical figures is difficult. Character development and unity of theme with the corresondance as a whole can hardly be on the mind of a scholar defending his reputation or satiating a lover. Yet these are exactly the criteria I default to in rating anything that tells a story.<br /><br />Yet the Letters of Abelard and Heloise earned four stars from me precisely because they made me forget that they are a historical correspondance. Abelard is a scholar before he is a theologian, and this gives him a specificity and a certain degree of honesty that many of his contemporaries lack (something that is especially visible in the first letter). His accounts of the politics imbued within the Medieval scholastic and monastic communities are utterly gripping. And, most importantly, the compelling relationship between Abelard and Heloise shines through each letter, growing only more potent as the personal details of the relationship are repressed beneath disputes on theological issues.<br /><br />In short, the Letters of Abelard and Heloise left me utterly and pleasantly surprised.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8931671560622845429" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


